  "prompt": "What is the best treatment for low latent inhibition?",
  "response": "Low Latent Inhibition (LLI) is not a medical condition with a standardized treatment, but rather a cognitive trait. Management typically involves:\n\n1. Psychological Support\n- Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT)\n- Counseling to develop coping strategies\n- Stress management techniques\n\n2. Educational Strategies\n- Personalized learning approaches\n- Structured environments\n- Breaking tasks into smaller steps\n\n3. Lifestyle Management\n- Regular sleep schedule\n- Healthy diet\n- Exercise\n- Mindfulness practices\n\n4. Potential Therapeutic Approaches\n- Medication for associated conditions (ADHD, anxiety)\n- Neurofeedback\n- Social skills training\n\n5. Strengths-Based Approach\n- Recognizing potential creative advantages\n- Developing problem-solving skills\n- Channeling heightened perceptual abilities positively\n\n6. Professional Guidance\n- Neuropsychological assessment\n- Individualized support plan\n- Ongoing monitoring\n\nIt's important to note that LLI is not a disorder, but a different cognitive processing style. Consulting with mental health professionals who understand individual neurodiversity can help develop the most appropriate personalized approach.",
